Now I see the full picture. Let me compare what Pi has vs what caveman-code does:

## What Pi Already Has

| Feature | Pi | How it works |
|---------|-----|-------------|
| **Tool truncation** | 2000 lines / 50KB | Basic head/tail truncation |
| **Grep truncation** | 500 chars/line | Per-line cap |
| **Compaction** | Auto-compaction | Summarizes old messages when context full |
| **Read dedup** | None | — |
| **ANSI strip** | None | — |
| **Terse output mode** | None | — |
| **Per-tool budgets** | None | Same limit for all tools |
| **Semantic extraction** | None | — |

## What Caveman-Code Does

| Layer | What it cuts | Savings |
|-------|-------------|---------|
| **Caveman Mode** | Model output filler (hedging, "Great question!", paragraphs) | ~9× less output tokens |
| **Tool Budgets** | bash: 80 lines, read: 300, grep: 120 | −67% to −94% tool output |
| **Read Dedup** | Re-reads return stub | −99% on repeats |
| **ANSI/blank collapse** | Color codes, empty lines | −18% to −50% |
| **RTK** | Bash output compression | −60% to −90% |

## What Pi Should Implement

### Tier 1 — Low effort, high impact (extensions)

**1. Terse Mode Extension** — Instruct model to reply with zero filler
```
pi.on("before_agent_start", (event) => ({
    systemPrompt: event.systemPrompt + "\n## Rules: Reply in terse fragments. No filler, no hedging, no paragraphs."
}));
```
**Impact:** −50%+ output tokens. Every turn the model reads back its own context.

**2. Per-Tool Budget Extension** — Override tool truncation per tool
```typescript
pi.on("tool_result", (event) => {
    if (event.toolName === "bash") return { content: truncate(event.content, { maxLines: 80 }) };
    if (event.toolName === "read") return { content: truncate(event.content, { maxLines: 300 }) };
    if (event.toolName === "grep") return { content: truncate(event.content, { maxLines: 120 }) };
});
```
**Impact:** −70%+ bash output. Most bash output is noise.

**3. Read Dedup Extension** — Fingerprint files, return stub on re-read
```typescript
const seen = new Map<string, string>();
pi.on("tool_result", (event) => {
    if (event.toolName === "read") {
        const hash = md5(event.content);
        if (seen.has(hash)) return { content: `[already read, ${event.content.length} chars]` };
        seen.set(hash, event.content);
    }
});
```
**Impact:** −99% on repeated reads. Agent often reads same file 3-5 times.

### Tier 2 — Medium effort, high impact (SDK features)

**4. ANSI Stripper** — Strip color codes from all tool output
```typescript
pi.on("tool_result", (event) => {
    if (event.toolName === "bash") {
        return { content: stripAnsi(event.content) };
    }
});
```
**Impact:** −18% to −50% on colored output.

**5. Blank Line Collapse** — Remove redundant blank lines
```typescript
pi.on("tool_result", (event) => {
    return { content: event.content.replace(/\n{3,}/g, "\n\n") };
});
```
**Impact:** −5% to −15%.

**6. Semantic Extraction** — For structured output (JSON, XML, test results), extract only relevant parts
```typescript
pi.on("tool_result", (event) => {
    if (event.toolName === "bash" && looksLikeJson(event.content)) {
        return { content: extractRelevantJson(event.content) };
    }
});
```
**Impact:** −60% on structured output.

### Tier 3 — High effort, highest impact (core changes)

**7. Per-Tool Configurable Budgets** — Let users configure tool output limits in settings.json
```json
{
    "toolBudgets": {
        "bash": { "maxLines": 80, "stripAnsi": true, "tailOnly": true },
        "read": { "maxLines": 300 },
        "grep": { "maxLines": 120, "maxLineLength": 200 }
    }
}
```
**Impact:** User-tunable compression. Default to aggressive.

**8. Context-Aware Truncation** — Don't just truncate at N lines, keep the parts the model is likely to need
```typescript
// For bash: keep last N lines (errors at the end)
// For read: keep lines around last edit location
// For grep: keep unique matches, dedup repeated patterns
```

**9. RTK Integration** — Optional bash output compression via external tool
```json
{
